-- French Stocks: ArcelorMittal, Peugeot, Renault, SocGen Move
-- B y   D a v i d   A l t a n e r
-- 2010-10-04T15:51:42Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-03/edf-ingenico-safran-zodiac-aerospace-may-move-french-equity-preview.html
France’s  CAC 40 Index  fell 42.28, or
1.2 percent, to 3,649.81 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Paris, a
sixth day of declines for the longest losing streak since
February 2009. The SBF 120 slid 1 percent to 2,723.86.  The following shares rose or fell in the French capital.
Stock symbols are in parentheses.  ArcelorMittal  (MT NA) dropped 3.1 percent to 23.55 euros.
Worldwide steel demand growth will slow next year as China’s
property market weakens and Japanese consumption falls,
according to the World Steel Association.  PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP), Europe’s second-biggest
carmaker, retreated 3.7 percent to 23.91 euros as auto shares
had the biggest decline among 19 European industry groups.
German new-car sales in September fell 18 percent to about
260,000 vehicles, the VDIK industry group said today.  Renault SA  (RNO FP) dropped 3.5 percent to 35.54 euros.  Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP) declined 1.3 percent to 40.85
euros. France’s second-biggest bank may consider smaller
acquisitions in international retail banking or private banking,
Handelsblatt said, citing an interview with deputy Chief
Executive Officer  Severin Cabannes .  Total SA  (FP FP) fell 1.4 percent to 37.53 euros.  Philippe Boisseau , head of gas and power at the company, said the market
for natural gas will become “very tight” in less than two or
three years.  To contact the reporter on this story:
